1. Business Problem Definition

Code City Cycles, a specialty mountain bike retailer, wants to identify which product categories generate the highest in-store sales and which categories provide the strongest margins. By analyzing product-level sales, category performance, and monthly sales trends, the shop can adjust purchasing to better match demand, prioritize profitable categories, and reduce capital tied up in slow-moving stock. This analysis supports data-driven inventory planning based on real customer buying behaviour at Code City Cycles.

2. Data Source Assessment

The dataset was exported directly from Lightspeed Retail POS, the in-store transaction system used by Code City Cycles. Three CSV files were downloaded: product-level category sales, daily sales, and category performance summaries. Lightspeed collects this data for operational and financial management, including inventory optimization, margin analysis, and shop-floor purchasing decisions. The data represents real retail activity during 20242025. Limitations include occasional missing cost fields for specific service items, but overall completeness and reliability make this dataset well-suited for business decision-making.

Data Source Attribution & URL

  • Data source: Lightspeed Retail POS CSV exports
  • Organization: Coal City Cycles
  • Vendor URL: https://www.lightspeedhq.com/

CSV Download Method: files exported from Lightspeed Retail POS and saved in the same folder as this R Markdown file.

Data Cleaning & Preparation

Cleaning Product-level Category Sales

category_sales <- category_sales %>%
mutate(
Total.Sold = as.numeric(Total.Sold),
Unit.Cost = as.numeric(Unit.Cost),
Total.Cost = as.numeric(Total.Cost),
Unit.Retail = as.numeric(Unit.Retail),
Total.Retail = as.numeric(Total.Retail),
Margin = as.numeric(Margin) # percentage (e.g., 52.81)
)

Cleaning Daily Sales Summary

daily_sales <- daily_sales %>%
  mutate(
    Date        = as.Date(sub(" UTC$", "", Date)),
    Sales.Count = as.numeric(Sales.Count),
    Subtotal    = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Subtotal)),
    Discounts   = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Discounts)),
    Total       = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Total)),
    Cost        = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Cost)),
    Profit      = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Profit)),
    MarginPct   = as.numeric(gsub("%", "", Margin)),
    
    Month       = floor_date(Date, unit = "month")
  )

Cleaning Category Performance Summary

category_summary <- category_summary %>%
  mutate(
    Subtotal              = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Subtotal)),
    Subtotal.w..Discounts = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Subtotal.w..Discounts)),
    Discounts             = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Discounts)),
    Total                 = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Total)),
    Cost                  = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Cost)),
    Profit                = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", Profit)),
    
    MarginPct             = as.numeric(gsub("%", "", Margin))
  )

Data Quality Assessment

Across 11,993 productcategory records, the dataset is approximately 99% complete. Missing values appear primarily in Unit.Cost and Unit.Retail (0.97%), which is expected for service items or non-inventory SKUs that do not have defined unit costs in Lightspeed. Only one margin value is missing (0.01%). These small gaps do not materially impact the analysis, especially with na.rm = TRUE applied in all aggregations. Lightspeed is a professional POS system widely used in the bike industry, providing reliable operational data to support purchasing decisions at Code City Cycles.

3. Comprehensive Data Analysis

Descriptive Analytics - Aggregate Summaries

Summary 1: Average Margin by Category

Interpretation: The category-level margin summary shows that several small-component groups - Brake Housing, Shifting, General shop supplies, and Seat Post - deliver exceptionally high margins, often above 90%. These categories contribute disproportionately to profitability despite representing lower-cost items. Tires, wheels, and brake-related parts also maintain strong average margins, indicating reliable profitability across common service-related products. This highlights the value of consistently stocking high-turnover, high-margin small parts to support both repair services and overall shop profitability.

category_margin_agg <- aggregate(
Margin ~ Category,
data = category_sales,
FUN = mean,
na.rm = TRUE
)
category_margin_agg <- category_margin_agg %>%
arrange(desc(Margin))
kable(head(category_margin_agg, 10),
digits = 2,
caption = "Top 10 Categories by Average Margin (%)") %>%
kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

Summary 2: Total Revenue and Units by Category

Interpretation: Revenue is dominated by complete bike sales, with Full Suspension, Hardtail, Gravel/Cross, and E-Bikes generating the largest dollar volumes despite relatively modest margins. In contrast, high-volume small-parts categories like General, Parts, Suspension, and Brakes produce substantial unit sales and significantly higher margins, making them major contributors to total profitability. This split indicates the shop relies on bikes for revenue but depends on parts and service-related categories for sustained margin performance and cash flow.

category_revenue_agg <- category_sales %>%
group_by(Category) %>%
summarise(
Total_Units = sum(Total.Sold, na.rm = TRUE),
Total_Revenue = sum(Total.Retail, na.rm = TRUE),
Avg_Margin = mean(Margin, na.rm = TRUE)
) %>%
arrange(desc(Total_Revenue))

Visual Analytics

Plot 1: Margin by Category (%)

Interpretation: This plot shows that small parts and service-related categoriessuch as Wheels, Shifting, Brakes, and General supplieshave the highest average margins, often above 8090%. These items consistently outperform complete bikes in profitability.

margin_plot_data <- category_summary %>%
filter(!is.na(MarginPct)) %>%
arrange(desc(MarginPct))
margin_plot_data <- margin_plot_data %>% slice_max(MarginPct, n = 15)
ggplot(margin_plot_data,
aes(x = reorder(Category, MarginPct), y = MarginPct)) +
geom_col(fill = accent) +
coord_flip() +
labs(
title = "Top Categories by Margin Percentage",
x = "Category",
y = "Average Margin (%)"
) +
theme_ev

Plot 2: Monthly Sales Trend

Interpretation: Revenue follows a strong seasonal pattern, climbing rapidly in spring and peaking in summer before dropping through the winter months. This reflects typical riding, competition, and repair cycles in a mountain bike retail environment.

monthly_sales <- daily_sales %>%
  mutate(
    Month = as.Date(floor_date(Date, unit = "month"))
  ) %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  summarise(
    Total_Revenue = sum(Total, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Profit  = sum(Profit, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
ggplot(monthly_sales, aes(x = Month, y = Total_Revenue)) +
  geom_line(color = accent, linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(color = accent, size = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "Monthly In-Store Revenue  Code City Cycles",
    x = "Month",
    y = "Total Revenue ($)"
  ) +
  scale_x_date(date_labels = "%b %Y") +
  theme_ev

Plot 3: Revenue Share by Category (Top 10)

Interpretation: Full suspension bikes generate the largest share of revenue, with other bike categories and key parts groups like Brakes, General items, and Suspension also making meaningful contributions to overall sales.

revenue_share <- category_revenue_agg %>%
mutate(Share = Total_Revenue / sum(Total_Revenue) * 100) %>%
arrange(desc(Share)) %>%
slice_max(Share, n = 10)

ggplot(revenue_share,
aes(x = "", y = Share, fill = Category)) +
geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
coord_polar("y") +
labs(
title = "Revenue Share by Category (Top 10)",
y = "Share (%)",
x = ""
) +
theme_void() +
theme(legend.position = "right")

Pattern Recognition

Category Profitability

High-margin small parts - such as Wheels, Shifting components, Brakes, and General shop supplies - consistently outperform complete bikes in profitability. These categories offer strong percentage margins and steady turnover, indicating they play a key role in sustaining overall shop profitability despite representing lower individual ticket values.

Seasonal Revenue

Sales show a clear seasonal cycle, with revenue peaking from late spring through midsummer and declining sharply in winter months. This pattern reflects predictable riding behavior and suggests that inventory levels, staffing, and purchasing should ramp up ahead of peak season and contract during slower winter periods.

4. Strategic Recommendations

Code City Cycles should align purchasing with both margin performance and seasonal demand. High-margin categories - such as Wheels, Shifting components, Brakes, and General small parts - should be kept well-stocked year-round, as they reliably support profitability and frequent service work. Complete bikes remain the largest revenue drivers, so pre-season orders for full-suspension, gravel, and hardtail models should be placed early to meet rising demand from spring through fall. Because competition season brings increased repairs and tune-ups, the shop should expand inventory of consumables and service-related parts before this period. During winter, purchasing can shift toward maintaining core essentials while focusing on service efficiency and planned maintenance rather than broad restocking.
